VALUES
(1, 49, 23, 23, 'kjv', 'The archers have sorely grieved him, and shot at him, and hated him:', 0, 68, 'connection', 'Suffering of the Righteous', 'This verse resonates with Psalm 22:12-13, where the psalmist describes being surrounded by strong bulls and fierce lions, illustrating the anguish and persecution faced by the righteous. The connection matters as it highlights the theme of unjust suffering that is prevalent throughout Scripture, underscoring the faithfulness of God even amidst trials.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Psalm 22:12-13", "description": "Describes the suffering and persecution faced by the righteous."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 49, 23, 23, 'kjv', 'The archers have sorely grieved him, and shot at him, and hated him:', 0, 68, 'theology', 'The Nature of Suffering', 'This passage suggests that suffering is often a part of God''s plan for His people. Many scholars believe that the reference to archers symbolizes those who oppose God’s chosen, reflecting the spiritual warfare faced by believers. This aligns with the broader Christian understanding of perseverance and reliance on God in times of distress.', 'sparkles', '[{"type": "commentary", "reference": "Matthew Henry''s Commentary", "description": "Explores the theological implications of suffering in the lives of the faithful."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 49, 23, 23, 'kjv', 'The archers have sorely grieved him, and shot at him, and hated him:', 0, 68, 'question', 'Understanding Persecution', 'What does this depiction of ''archers'' teach us about the nature of our enemies? In what ways can we discern spiritual opposition in our own lives, and how does this understanding affect our response to such challenges?', 'questionmark.circle.fill', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 49, 23, 23, 'kjv', 'The archers have sorely grieved him, and shot at him, and hated him:', 0, 68, 'greek', 'Understanding Grief', 'חָלַל (chalal, H2490) - to pierce, to wound, to bore through. This term conveys a deep sense of injury and vulnerability, emphasizing the emotional and physical pain inflicted upon the subject. This adds depth to the understanding of grief as not merely emotional but also physical in the context of persecution.', 'textformat.abc', '[{"type": "strongs", "reference": "H2490", "description": "Strong''s number for the Hebrew term used in this context."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 49, 24, 24, 'kjv', 'But his bow abode in strength', 0, 29, 'theology', 'Strength in Adversity', 'This phrase illustrates the resilience that can be found through faith. Many scholars believe that Joseph''s ability to remain strong in the face of adversity reflects a deeper theological truth: the sustaining power of God in our trials. This aligns with biblical teachings that emphasize reliance on divine strength during tough times (see Philippians 4:13).', 'person.2.fill', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Philippians 4:13", "description": "I can do all things through Christ who strengthens me."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 49, 24, 24, 'kjv', 'the arms of his hands were made strong', 35, 73, 'greek', 'Strength from God', 'יד (yad, H3027) - hand, power, strength. The term ''hands'' signifies not only physical strength but also the means by which God accomplishes His will through us. This connection emphasizes that true strength derives from God''s empowerment, echoing themes found throughout Scripture.', 'textformat.abc', '[{"type": "strongs", "reference": "H3027", "description": "Strong''s number for ''hand'' in Hebrew."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 49, 24, 24, 'kjv', 'by the hands of the mighty God of Jacob', 74, 113, 'connection', 'God as Protector', 'This phrase connects to Psalm 46:1, which describes God as our refuge and strength. The reference to ''the mighty God of Jacob'' highlights God''s historical role as a protector of His people, reinforcing the covenant relationship established with Jacob''s descendants. This connection is vital as it reassures believers of God’s steadfast support.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Psalm 46:1", "description": "God is our refuge and strength, a very present help in trouble."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 49, 24, 24, 'kjv', '(from thence is the shepherd, the stone of Israel:)', 115, 166, 'question', 'Who is the Shepherd?', 'In what ways does referring to God as ''the shepherd'' and ''the stone of Israel'' shape our understanding of His guidance and stability in our lives? This image invites reflection on the nature of Christ as the Good Shepherd (John 10:11) and the cornerstone of our faith (1 Peter 2:6).', 'lightbulb', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 49, 25, 25, 'kjv', 'by the God of thy father', 5, 29, 'connection', 'Fatherly Divine Support', 'This phrase echoes the covenantal relationship established in Genesis 17:7, where God promises to be a God to Abraham and his descendants. It underscores the continuity of divine aid through generations. The mention of ''father'' ties Joseph''s blessings to the patriarchal lineage, highlighting the importance of familial faith and the assurance that God supports those in covenant with Him.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Genesis 17:7", "description": "God''s covenant with Abraham and his descendants"}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 49, 25, 25, 'kjv', 'bless thee with blessings of heaven above', 83, 124, 'theology', 'Heavenly Blessings', 'This passage suggests that God''s blessings encompass both spiritual and material realms, reflecting a holistic view of divine providence. Many scholars believe that the ''blessings of heaven'' symbolize God''s favor and abundance, which are essential for both physical needs and spiritual growth, emphasizing the comprehensive nature of God''s provision.', 'sparkles', NULL, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 49, 25, 25, 'kjv', 'blessings of the breasts, and of the womb', 166, 207, 'greek', 'Fertility and Nurturing', 'בְּרָכֹת (berakhot, H1293) - blessings, prosperity, favor. This Hebrew term highlights the significance of fertility and nurturing, both physically and spiritually, in the context of family and community. The blessings of the womb symbolize not just physical offspring but also the continuation of God’s promises through future generations.', 'textformat.abc', '[{"type": "strongs", "reference": "H1293", "description": "Strong''s number for blessings"}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 49, 25, 25, 'kjv', 'who shall help thee', 31, 50, 'question', 'Divine Assistance Reflection', 'What does it mean to rely on God as your helper in times of need? As Joseph''s blessings are pronounced, how can you apply the assurance of divine help to your own life challenges? Reflecting on this promise can lead to deeper trust in God''s provision and support.', 'questionmark.circle.fill', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 49, 26, 26, 'kjv', 'The blessings of thy father have prevailed above the blessings of my progenitors', 0, 80, 'connection', 'Blessings in Scripture', 'This phrase connects with Deuteronomy 33:13-17, where Moses blesses the tribes of Israel, emphasizing the significance of paternal blessings within the covenant community. It illustrates the continuity of God''s favor from one generation to another, highlighting how Joseph''s blessings surpass those of his forefathers, reinforcing his special role in God''s plan.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Deuteronomy 33:13-17", "description": "Moses'' blessings to the tribes, including Joseph"}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 49, 26, 26, 'kjv', 'the utmost bound of the everlasting hills', 86, 127, 'theology', 'Symbolism of Endurance', 'The imagery of ''everlasting hills'' suggests stability and permanence, reflecting God''s eternal covenant with His people. Many scholars believe this symbolizes the unshakeable nature of God''s promises, emphasizing that the blessings bestowed upon Joseph are not temporary but are established for eternity, pointing to the enduring nature of divine favor.', 'sparkles', NULL, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 49, 26, 26, 'kjv', 'on the crown of the head of him that was separate from his brethren', 170, 237, 'question', 'Significance of Separation', 'What does it mean for Joseph to be ''separate from his brethren'' in the context of God''s blessings? How does this separation reflect God''s purpose for Joseph in the larger narrative of Genesis and the unfolding of Israel''s history?', 'questionmark.circle.fill', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 49, 26, 26, 'kjv', 'The blessings of thy father', 0, 27, 'greek', 'Blessing in Hebrew', 'בָּרָכָה (berakhah, H1293) - blessing, gift. This term denotes not just a verbal blessing but also the impartation of divine favor and prosperity, indicating a deep spiritual significance that transcends mere words.', 'textformat.abc', '[{"type": "strongs", "reference": "H1293", "description": "Strong''s number for ''blessing'' in Hebrew"}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 49, 27, 27, 'kjv', 'Benjamin shall ravin as a wolf:', 0, 31, 'connection', 'Symbolism of Benjamin', 'The imagery of Benjamin as a wolf connects with other biblical references that portray wolves as fierce and cunning. For example, in Jeremiah 5:6, wolves are described as predators that instill fear. This connection emphasizes Benjamin''s strength and ferocity, characteristics that would define the tribe''s future. Understanding this symbolism sheds light on the nature of Benjamin''s descendants and their role in Israel''s history.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Jeremiah 5:6", "description": "Wolves represent danger and strength."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 49, 27, 27, 'kjv', 'in the morning he shall devour the prey,', 32, 72, 'theology', 'Divine Providence in Strength', 'This passage suggests that Benjamin''s strength is not merely a trait but a reflection of God’s providence in his life. Many scholars believe that the ''morning'' symbolizes new beginnings or opportunities where God''s provision is evident. This illustrates a theological theme that God equips His people for their battles, empowering them to seize opportunities presented to them.', 'sparkles', NULL, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 49, 27, 27, 'kjv', 'and at night he shall divide the spoil.', 73, 112, 'question', 'Understanding the Spoils', 'What does the act of ''dividing the spoil'' reveal about the nature of victory and community among the tribes of Israel? This phrase prompts reflection on the importance of sharing blessings and resources within a community after overcoming challenges. How can this principle of shared victory apply to our lives today?', 'lightbulb', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 49, 28, 28, 'kjv', 'All these are the twelve tribes of Israel:', 0, 42, 'connection', 'Twelve Tribes Reference', 'The reference to the twelve tribes of Israel links directly to Exodus 24:4, where Moses writes down all the words of the Lord and builds an altar with twelve pillars representing these tribes. This connection highlights the foundational role of the tribes in Israel''s identity and covenant relationship with God.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Exodus 24:4", "description": "Moses records the covenant with twelve pillars representing the tribes."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 49, 28, 28, 'kjv', 'and this is it that their father spake unto them, and blessed them;', 43, 110, 'theology', 'Significance of Blessing', 'This passage suggests the importance of paternal blessing in biblical culture. Many scholars believe that blessings conveyed not only favor but also destiny and identity, shaping the future of the tribes. This reflects the broader theological theme of blessing as a divine act that carries weight in the unfolding plan of God.', 'sparkles', NULL, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 49, 28, 28, 'kjv', 'every one according to his blessing he blessed them.', 111, 163, 'question', 'Personal Reflection on Blessings', 'What might it mean for you to receive a blessing tailored specifically to your identity and purpose? How does understanding the unique blessings given to each tribe inform your view of God’s plans for individuals today?', 'lightbulb', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 49, 28, 28, 'kjv', 'All these are the twelve tribes of Israel:', 0, 42, 'greek', 'Hebrew Roots of ''Israel''', 'יִשְׂרָאֵל (Yisra''el, H3478) - God contends, or he struggles with God. This name signifies not only the nation but also the relationship between God and His people, emphasizing the divine purpose behind their trials and triumphs.', 'character.book.closed', '[{"type": "strongs", "reference": "H3478", "description": "Strong''s number for the name Israel."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 49, 29, 29, 'kjv', 'I am to be gathered unto my people:', 41, 76, 'theology', 'Gathering of God''s People', 'This phrase reflects a significant theological concept regarding the afterlife and the community of believers. Many scholars believe that Jacob''s understanding of being ''gathered'' indicates a reunion with his ancestors, suggesting a continuity of identity and faith across generations. This notion is echoed in Matthew 22:32, where Jesus speaks of God being the God of the living, affirming life beyond death.', 'person.2.fill', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Matthew 22:32", "description": "Jesus'' affirmation of resurrection and connection with the faithful"}]'::jsonb, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 49, 29, 29, 'kjv', 'bury me with my fathers', 77, 100, 'connection', 'Covenantal Continuity', 'The request to be buried with his fathers highlights the importance of ancestral connections and the continuity of God''s covenant. This can be connected to Genesis 50:24-26, where Joseph expresses a similar wish to be buried in Canaan, emphasizing the faith in God''s promises regarding the land. Such connections reinforce the theme of belonging and inheritance within the covenant community.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Genesis 50:24-26", "description": "Joseph''s desire to be buried in Canaan, linking to God''s promises"}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 49, 29, 29, 'kjv', 'the cave that is in the field of Ephron the Hittite,', 104, 156, 'greek', 'Significance of Burial Place', 'The Hebrew term for ''cave'' is ''מְעָרָה'' (me''arah, H4631) - cave, den, or shelter. This signifies not just a physical location but a sacred space, underscoring the importance of burial sites in Israelite tradition. Burial in a familial plot symbolizes both respect for ancestors and a physical claim to the land promised by God.', 'textformat.abc', '[{"type": "strongs", "reference": "H4631", "description": "Hebrew word for ''cave'' related to burial practices"}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 49, 29, 29, 'kjv', 'I am to be gathered unto my people:', 41, 76, 'question', 'Understanding Afterlife Promises', 'What does it mean to be ''gathered'' unto one''s people in the context of faith? How does this understanding influence our perspective on death and community in the body of Christ today?', 'lightbulb', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 49, 30, 30, 'kjv', 'In the cave that is in the field of Machpelah', 0, 45, 'connection', 'Connection to Abraham''s Legacy', 'This reference to Machpelah connects to Genesis 23:19, where Abraham secures this burial site. The significance of this location as a family tomb underscores the importance of land and legacy in God''s covenant with Abraham. It symbolizes the promise of the land to his descendants and God''s faithfulness to His promises.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Genesis 23:19", "description": "Abraham''s purchase of Machpelah for burial"}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 49, 30, 30, 'kjv', 'which is before Mamre, in the land of Canaan', 47, 91, 'theology', 'Theological Significance of Canaan', 'This passage emphasizes the land of Canaan as the promised inheritance for Abraham''s descendants. Many scholars believe this foreshadows the broader theological theme of God''s promised land throughout Scripture, culminating in the New Testament understanding of spiritual inheritance for believers (Hebrews 11:8-10).', 'sparkles', '[{"type": "commentary", "reference": "Hebrews 11:8-10", "description": "Explores the faith of Abraham regarding promised land"}]'::jsonb, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 49, 30, 30, 'kjv', 'which Abraham bought with the field of Ephron the Hittite', 93, 150, 'question', 'Understanding Ownership and Promise', 'What does it mean for Abraham to purchase this land in the context of God''s promise? How does this act of buying a burial site reflect the deeper spiritual truths about faith, obedience, and the anticipation of God''s promises being fulfilled in our lives?', 'lightbulb', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 49, 31, 31, 'kjv', 'There they buried Abraham and Sarah his wife;', 0, 45, 'connection', 'Abraham''s Burial Connection', 'This phrase connects to Genesis 23:19, where Abraham purchases the cave of Machpelah specifically for burial purposes. This emphasizes the significance of the land as a family burial site and God''s promise of land to Abraham''s descendants. It also highlights the respect and honor given to the patriarchs in death, reflecting their covenant relationship with God.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Genesis 23:19", "description": "Details Abraham''s purchase of the burial site."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 49, 31, 31, 'kjv', 'there they buried Isaac and Rebekah his wife;', 46, 91, 'theology', 'Covenant Continuation', 'This passage suggests the continuity of God''s covenant through the generations, as Isaac and Rebekah are also honored in the same burial site as Abraham and Sarah. Many scholars believe this signifies the importance of family lineage and the faithfulness of God in maintaining His promises across generations.', 'sparkles', NULL, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 49, 31, 31, 'kjv', 'and there I buried Leah.', 92, 116, 'question', 'Leah''s Legacy Reflection', 'Why is Leah''s burial mentioned alongside the matriarchs? What does this reveal about her role in Jacob''s family and the broader narrative of God''s chosen people? Consider how Leah''s story, often overshadowed by Rachel''s, contributes to the understanding of God''s providence and grace in familial relationships.', 'questionmark.circle.fill', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 49, 32, 32, 'kjv', 'The purchase of the field and of the cave that is therein was from the children of Heth.', 0, 88, 'connection', 'Historical Purchase Significance', 'This verse highlights the importance of land ownership in the biblical context, paralleling Genesis 23:16-20 where Abraham negotiates for a burial site. Such transactions underscore the significance of the land of Canaan to the patriarchs and their descendants, serving as a foundational promise of the land to Israel.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Genesis 23:16-20", "description": "Abraham''s purchase of the cave of Machpelah, establishing a family burial ground."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 49, 32, 32, 'kjv', 'children of Heth', 71, 87, 'theology', 'Covenantal Implications', 'The mention of the ''children of Heth'' signifies the ongoing interaction between God''s chosen people and the surrounding nations. This passage suggests God''s providential care in providing a physical space for His people, which is a precursor to the broader theme of land as a part of God''s covenant with Abraham and his descendants.', 'sparkles', NULL, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 49, 32, 32, 'kjv', 'The purchase of the field', 0, 25, 'question', 'Understanding Ownership', 'What does the act of purchasing land signify in the context of God''s promises to His people? How does this reflect on our understanding of stewardship and belonging within God''s plan?', 'lightbulb', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 49, 32, 32, 'kjv', 'was from the children of Heth.', 58, 88, 'greek', 'Hebrew Context', 'חִתִּי (Hittite, H2845) - a member of an ancient civilization known for its alliances and conflicts with Israel. Understanding the Hittites in this context sheds light on the complexities of Israel''s relationship with surrounding nations.', 'textformat.abc', '[{"type": "strongs", "reference": "H2845", "description": "Strong''s number for Hittite, providing insights into their historical context."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 49, 33, 33, 'kjv', 'yielded up the ghost', 97, 117, 'greek', 'Original Language Insight', 'The phrase ''yielded up the ghost'' can be connected to the Greek word ἐκδίδωμι (ekdídōmi, G1544) which means ''to give up'' or ''to deliver.'' This term emphasizes the act of relinquishing life and can be seen in the context of Christ''s own yielding of His spirit (Luke 23:46). This connection highlights the gravity and intentionality of Jacob''s final moments.', 'textformat.abc', '[{"type": "strongs", "reference": "G1544", "description": "Greek term for ''to give up'' or ''to deliver''"}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 49, 33, 33, 'kjv', 'gathered unto his people', 127, 151, 'connection', 'Connection to Afterlife Belief', 'The phrase ''gathered unto his people'' resonates with the concept of familial unity in death, aligning with Genesis 25:8 where Abraham is said to be ''gathered to his people.'' This connection illustrates the belief in a communal afterlife among the patriarchs, reinforcing the biblical theme of continuity in the covenant community.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Genesis 25:8", "description": "Abraham''s death and gathering to his people"}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 49, 33, 33, 'kjv', 'made an end of commanding his sons', 19, 53, 'theology', 'Importance of Final Instructions', 'This passage suggests the theological significance of a father''s final words to his children. Many scholars believe that Jacob''s commands reflect the passing of authority and blessing, similar to the concept of patriarchal succession seen throughout Scripture. This highlights the importance of imparting wisdom and guidance across generations.', 'person.2.fill', NULL, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 49, 33, 33, 'kjv', 'gathered up his feet into the bed', 58, 91, 'question', 'Reflection on Dying Well', 'What does it mean to ''gather up his feet into the bed'' in the context of dying well? How can we reflect on our own lives and the legacy we leave behind as we approach the end? This image invites a meditation on the peace and readiness that should accompany our final moments.', 'lightbulb', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 50, 1, 1, 'kjv', 'And Joseph fell upon his father’s face, and wept upon him, and kissed him.', 0, 74, 'connection', 'Father-Son Relationships', 'Joseph''s deep grief is reminiscent of David''s lament over Absalom in 2 Samuel 18:33, where a father mourns his son. This connection highlights the profound pain of loss and the depth of familial bonds, illustrating that such relationships can evoke deep emotions within biblical narratives.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "2 Samuel 18:33", "description": "David''s lament for Absalom demonstrates the sorrow of a father losing a son."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 50, 1, 1, 'kjv', 'And Joseph fell upon his father’s face, and wept upon him, and kissed him.', 0, 74, 'theology', 'Grief and Mourning', 'This passage suggests a theological understanding of grief as a natural and necessary response to loss. Many scholars believe that mourning is not only permissible but also an important part of the healing process, reflecting the humanity of even the most revered biblical figures.', 'person.2.fill', NULL, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 50, 1, 1, 'kjv', 'wept upon him', 44, 57, 'question', 'Understanding Grief', 'What does Joseph''s act of weeping reveal about the nature of his relationship with his father, and how can we apply this understanding of grief to our own experiences of loss?', 'heart.text.square', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 50, 1, 1, 'kjv', 'kissed him', 63, 73, 'greek', 'Kissing in Scripture', 'καταφιλέω (kataphileō, G2705) - to kiss affectionately. This term emphasizes the intimacy and love inherent in Joseph''s actions, showing that physical expressions of love are significant in the biblical context.', 'textformat.abc', '[{"type": "strongs", "reference": "G2705", "description": "Strong''s number for ''to kiss affectionately.''"}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 50, 2, 2, 'kjv', 'And Joseph commanded his servants the physicians to embalm his father:', 0, 70, 'connection', 'Embalming in Egyptian Culture', 'The practice of embalming in Genesis 50:2 reflects the Egyptian customs surrounding death and the afterlife, as seen in Exodus 13:19, where Joseph''s bones are carried to the Promised Land. This connection highlights the reverence for the dead in Egyptian culture and foreshadows Israel''s eventual exodus. Understanding this cultural background enriches our appreciation for Joseph''s actions and the significance of honoring his father.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Exodus 13:19", "description": "Joseph''s bones are mentioned, emphasizing the importance of his father''s burial customs."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 50, 2, 2, 'kjv', 'the physicians embalmed Israel.', 75, 106, 'greek', 'Embalming in Context', 'The term ''embalm'' in the original Hebrew is חָנַט (ḥānāṭ, H2580) - to embalm or preserve. This term indicates a process deeply rooted in the culture of ancient Egypt, showing how Joseph, though a Hebrew, embraced certain practices for the sake of his father''s dignity. This reflects a broader theological theme of God''s people engaging with and transforming surrounding cultures.', 'textformat.abc', '[{"type": "strongs", "reference": "H2580", "description": "Strong''s definition of the Hebrew term for embalm."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 50, 2, 2, 'kjv', 'Joseph commanded his servants the physicians', 4, 48, 'theology', 'Authority and Respect', 'This passage illustrates Joseph''s authority and his respectful care for his father, Israel. Many scholars believe this reflects a foundational aspect of familial duty in biblical theology, where honoring one’s parents is paramount (Exodus 20:12). Joseph’s actions serve as a model of respect and love, emphasizing the importance of family relationships within a covenant community.', 'sparkles', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Exodus 20:12", "description": "The commandment to honor one''s parents."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 50, 2, 2, 'kjv', 'And Joseph commanded his servants', 0, 33, 'question', 'Leadership and Care', 'What does Joseph''s command to his servants reveal about his character and leadership style? How can we apply his example of compassion and responsibility in our own roles, whether in family, work, or community?', 'questionmark.circle.fill', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 50, 3, 3, 'kjv', 'forty days were fulfilled for him;', 4, 38, 'connection', 'Significance of Mourning Period', 'The forty days of mourning for Jacob resonate with the biblical theme of mourning periods, similar to Moses'' mourning for Aaron in Deuteronomy 34:8, which lasted thirty days. This connection emphasizes the importance of honoring the dead among the Israelites and reflects a cultural practice shared throughout biblical narratives.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Deuteronomy 34:8", "description": "Moses mourns for Aaron, highlighting mourning customs."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini');